  "prompt": "What's the story behind Apple's half eaten apple fruit logo?",
  "response": "The Apple logo was designed by Rob Janoff in 1977. Contrary to popular myths, the bite taken out of the apple was not a reference to Alan Turing (a computer pioneer who died by cyanide poisoning), nor was it a play on the word \"byte.\"\n\nAccording to Janoff himself, the bite was simply a design decision to ensure people would recognize it as an apple and not a cherry or other round fruit. The original logo was rainbow-colored when first introduced, reflecting the Apple II computer's color capabilities, and later evolved to the monochromatic version we know today.\n\nSteve Jobs reportedly liked the logo and approved it quickly. The simplicity and memorability of the design have made it one of the most recognizable corporate logos in the world.\n\nOver the years, the logo has become a symbol of innovation, creativity, and sleek design, closely associated with Apple's brand identity and technological aesthetic.",
